title: Stata for Mac Kernel Restarts
body:
I am having two issues, one partially resolved one and one outstanding, both with Stata for Mac.

I am running Stata IC currently on the Mojave Beta, with the most recent Anaconda distribution (`python --version` returns `Python 3.6.5 :: Anaconda, Inc.`) though the same issues were occurring on High Sierra.

1) After running `python -m stata_kernel.install` I got the configuration error. I opened up the `.stata_kernel.conf` file and edited line 5 to read:

`stata_path = /Applications/Stata/StataIC.app/Contents/MacOS/StataIC`

Rerunning `python -m stata_kernel.install` I get the following error:

```
Installing Jupyter kernel spec
WARNING: Could not find Stata path.
Refer to the documentation to see how to set it manually:

https://kylebarron.github.io/stata_kernel/getting_started/#configuration
```

I am able to partially remedy this by renaming the app from `Stata IC` to just Stata. Rerunning `python -m stata_kernel.install` it installs correctly, the `.stata_kernel.conf` file fixes itself to read:
`stata_path = /Applications/Stata/Stata.app/Contents/MacOS/StataIC`

Based on this I thought I had solved the issue and tried launching a Jupyter Notebook.  This is when the second issue arises:

2) Once I start a Jupyter Notebook with Stata as the language Stata launches, but then I get repeating crashes and the following error in Jupyter Notebook:
`The kernel appears to have died. It will restart automatically.`

This goes into a loop where Stata continually restarts until I shut down the kernel from Jupyter Notebook. Below is the error code when starting the kernel and then through one restart (though these restarts will loop if left unattended. Please let me know what else I can do to troubleshoot this problem or if there is more info I can provide to diagnose.

I have been using stata_kernel on Windows and love it, though I much prefer running MacOS when possible. If this is diagnosable and fixable I would love to be able to use it on Mac, though understand that you are likely busy and that this may not be a priority.

Thanks!

Greg
